            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Nico Reyes was born of fog and steel, a product of San Francisco\u2019s working-class soul. Raised in the Outer Sunset by his Filipino father, a former Navy mechanic, and his Irish-American mother, a city hall clerk, Nico\u2019s upbringing was a blend of cultures, cuisines, and the constant, rhythmic roar of the Pacific. He was never one for books; his hands, however, understood the world in a way his mind struggled to. While his peers stressed over SAT scores, Nico found his calling in the sparks of his high school\u2019s metal shop.\n\nA guidance counselor, seeing Nico\u2019s talent and disinterest in academia, steered him toward a vocational program post-graduation. It was a pivotal moment that saved him from a future of aimless jobs. He thrived in an environment of grinders, welders, and raw materials, apprenticing under an old master fabricator in the Dogpatch. The work was demanding but honest. When his father passed away in his late twenties, Nico poured his grief into his craft, finding solace in the heat of the forge and the precision of a perfect weld.\n\nNow, at 41, Nico is a respected custom metal fabricator. His days begin before the sun burns through the Sunset\u2019s marine layer. He kickstarts his vintage Triumph motorcycle, the engine\u2019s growl a familiar alarm clock for his neighbors. The 8.5-mile commute to his shared workshop in the Dogpatch is his daily meditation, a gritty ballet through city traffic. He spends his days transforming cold steel into custom gates, furniture, and architectural elements for clients who value his artistry.\n\nHis social life is small but solid, built around a weekly poker game with other tradesmen and long rides with his motorcycle crew along the coastal highways. He\u2019s a regular at a no-frills bar in his neighborhood, a man who has watched the city gentrify around him with a mix of resentment and weary acceptance. Nico\u2019s dream isn\u2019t wealth, but permanence. He hopes to one day buy the building his workshop occupies, securing his place in a city that increasingly pushes out its makers. His ultimate aspiration is to be commissioned for a large, public sculpture\u2014a permanent mark of his own, welded into the heart of the city that forged him."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 16, staring through the dark glass of a welding helmet in his high school metal shop. The world outside vanished. There was only the electric hiss and the blinding, sun-like glow as he drew a bead, joining two pieces of scrap steel. When he lifted the helmet, the glowing red line was perfect, seamless. It wasn't just metal; it was a feeling of profound, sudden rightness. For the first time, something made absolute sense to him, a language his hands spoke fluently. It was the moment his future began.\n\n***\n\n2.\nAt ten years old, he\u2019d watch his father\u2019s hands\u2014strong, scarred, stained with grease\u2014methodically disassemble and repair a ship\u2019s pump on their back patio. His dad never spoke much, but his movements were a lecture on patience and integrity. Nico saw how a complex machine could be understood, respected, and made whole again through sheer will and skill. He realized then that building and fixing things was a kind of noble truth, a legacy passed down not in words, but in the quiet confidence of capable hands.\n\n***\n\n3.\nThe night after his father's funeral, sleep was impossible. Just past 2 a.m., he rode to the empty Dogpatch workshop. Under the bare bulbs, he grabbed two heavy plates of scrap steel. He didn't design, he just welded. He laid bead after furious bead, the heat on his face a welcome sting, the roar of the arc drowning out his grief. By dawn, he had a solid, ugly, indestructible cube of metal. It was his sorrow given form, and the act of creating it was the only thing that held him together.\n\n***\n\n4.\nHe spent a year rebuilding the '71 Triumph, piece by painstaking piece. The first time he kicked it over and the engine roared to life, the sound vibrated through his entire body. He took it across the Golden Gate Bridge, the salty wind tearing at his jacket. As he looked back at the city skyline shrouded in fog, he felt a sharp, pure sense of freedom. He wasn't just riding a motorcycle; he was riding his own creation, a machine of escape built with his own two hands.\n\n***\n\n5.\nHe saw it on his ride home last fall\u2014a small, discreet \"For Sale\" sign on the brick wall of his workshop building. It felt like a physical blow. The abstract threat of being displaced suddenly had a price tag and a phone number. In that moment, his quiet ambition to own the building became a fierce, urgent need. The sign wasn't just about real estate; it was a challenge, a reminder that in the new San Francisco, even a life built of steel could be erased overnight."
